"Romeo and Juliet," a tragedy by William Shakespeare, tells the story of two young lovers from feuding families in Verona, the Montagues and the Capulets. Romeo Montague falls in love with Juliet Capulet at a masked ball, and they secretly marry the next day. However, a series of misunderstandings and tragic events unfold, including the banishment of Romeo after he kills Juliet's cousin Tybalt in a duel. In a desperate attempt to reunite, Juliet fakes her death, but the plan goes awry. Believing she is truly dead, Romeo takes his own life. When Juliet awakens and finds Romeo dead beside her, she also takes her life. Their tragic deaths ultimately reconcile their families, highlighting the senselessness of their feud.
